        multiple times in a loop, and each time it will do some work, i.e.
        producing some output (in ``outbuf``) or consuming some input (from ``inbuf``) or
        both. If its not possible to do any work an error is returned.

        Note that a single call may not consume all input (or any input at all).
        Also a call may produce output even if given no input, due to state stored
        in the converter producing output.

        If any data was either produced or consumed, and then an error happens, then
        only the successful conversion is reported and the error is returned on the
        next call.

        A full conversion loop involves calling this method repeatedly, each time
        giving it new input and space output space. When there is no more input
        data after the data in ``inbuf``, the flag :data:`Gio.ConverterFlags.INPUT_AT_END` must be set.
        The loop will be (unless some error happens) returning :data:`Gio.ConverterResult.CONVERTED`
        each time until all data is consumed and all output is produced, then
        :data:`Gio.ConverterResult.FINISHED` is returned instead. Note, that :data:`Gio.ConverterResult.FINISHED`
        may be returned even if :data:`Gio.ConverterFlags.INPUT_AT_END` is not set, for instance
        in a decompression converter where the end of data is detectable from the
        data (and there might even be other data after the end of the compressed data).

        When some data has successfully been converted ``bytes_read`` and is set to
        the number of bytes read from ``inbuf``, and ``bytes_written`` is set to indicate
        how many bytes was written to ``outbuf``. If there are more data to output
        or consume (i.e. unless the :data:`Gio.ConverterFlags.INPUT_AT_END` is specified) then
        :data:`Gio.ConverterResult.CONVERTED` is returned, and if no more data is to be output
        then :data:`Gio.ConverterResult.FINISHED` is returned.

        On error :data:`Gio.ConverterResult.ERROR` is returned and ``error`` is set accordingly.
        Some errors need special handling:

        :data:`Gio.IOErrorEnum.NO_SPACE` is returned if there is not enough space
        to write the resulting converted data, the application should
        call the function again with a larger ``outbuf`` to continue.

        :data:`Gio.IOErrorEnum.PARTIAL_INPUT` is returned if there is not enough
        input to fully determine what the conversion should produce,
        and the :data:`Gio.ConverterFlags.INPUT_AT_END` flag is not set. This happens for
        example with an incomplete multibyte sequence when converting text,
        or when a regexp matches up to the end of the input (and may match
        further input). It may also happen when ``inbuf_size`` is zero and
        there is no more data to produce.

        When this happens the application should read more input and then
        call the function again. If further input shows that there is no
        more data call the function again with the same data but with
        the :data:`Gio.ConverterFlags.INPUT_AT_END` flag set. This may cause the conversion
        to finish as e.g. in the regexp match case (or, to fail again with
        :data:`Gio.IOErrorEnum.PARTIAL_INPUT` in e.g. a charset conversion where the
        input is actually partial).

        After :meth:`Gio.Converter.convert` has returned :data:`Gio.ConverterResult.FINISHED` the
        converter object is in an invalid state where its not allowed
        to call :meth:`Gio.Converter.convert` anymore. At this time you can only
