        """
        This function should be called by any :class:`Gio.VolumeMonitor`
        implementation when a new :class:`Gio.Mount` object is created that is not
        associated with a :class:`Gio.Volume` object. It must be called just before
        emitting the ``mount_added`` signal.

        If the return value is not ``None``, the caller must associate the
        returned :class:`Gio.Volume` object with the :class:`Gio.Mount`. This involves returning
        it in its :meth:`Gio.Mount.get_volume` implementation. The caller must
        also listen for the "removed" signal on the returned object
        and give up its reference when handling that signal

        Similarly, if implementing :meth:`Gio.VolumeMonitor.adopt_orphan_mount`,
        the implementor must take a reference to ``mount`` and return it in
        its :meth:`Gio.Volume.get_mount` implemented. Also, the implementor must
        listen for the "unmounted" signal on ``mount`` and give up its
        reference upon handling that signal.

        There are two main use cases for this function.

        One is when implementing a user space file system driver that reads
        blocks of a block device that is already represented by the native
        volume monitor (for example a CD Audio file system driver). Such
        a driver will generate its own :class:`Gio.Mount` object that needs to be
        associated with the :class:`Gio.Volume` object that represents the volume.

        The other is for implementing a :class:`Gio.VolumeMonitor` whose sole purpose
        is to return :class:`Gio.Volume` objects representing entries in the users
        "favorite servers" list or similar.
        """
    @staticmethod
    def get() -> VolumeMonitor:
        """
        Gets the volume monitor used by gio.
        """
